e to feed and educate.  When it comes to Israel, this country wasn't put together for religious purposes.  This country was put together to protect a group of people from persecution.  They still have freedom of religion in that country despite being labeled a &quot;Jewish State&quot;.  They just need to retain Jewish majority because they are a democracy, and if too many non-Jews are voted in by the majority, then the people lose their protection and risk anything from persecution to another Holocaust.  Many of the Jews living there are totally secular and many are atheist.  This also goes for the politicians, and some of the politicians are Muslim Arabs.  A lot of people see this as a religious state, but no religious practice or belief is dictated from the government.  They just don't necessarily have SOCAS, but neither do the European nations.  Israel is high up on the aid list, but this benefits the US in that we have an ally in the Mid East and the education system over there helps to produce scientists and such that work with the US to further mankind's progress.  Egypt also receives a lot of US aid, and eventhough we get a lot of terrorists out of that country, the better we can make that country in terms of education and such, the less their problems will be thrown our way, not to mention great people come out of these oppressed countries when they are provided with the advancements that America offers.   Dictating that Egypt steer away from human rights violations is one thing, but dictating that they set up their laws just like our's hurts the Egyptians, and ultimately has a negative effect on the US.  Our laws apply within these borders alone, and the only time we have a right to tell people to change is when others are getting hurt.  If we pull funds from every country that lacks SOCAS, then we would stand alone.  JMO.<br>
<br>
Stacey <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#b9a1d0><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/breligiousdebate60574.showUserPublicProfile?gid=pagels@religiousdebate60574>Pagels</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 41<br> <font color=#3333ff>(2/18/03 2:20 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=119.topic&index=11>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  political question</span><hr size=1> The thing is, having an official religion plays little role in how religious the citizens are. <br>
