<br>
It is appropriate because the very nations that are outspoken about Israel's treatment of Arabs are a heck of a lot worse.  They are hypocrites.  The so-called facts regarding this whole issue are coming out of these very nations.  Yes, Israel does have more to live up to than their neighbors, but why should they have more to live up to than all the other democracies in the world?  Sure, every nation should constantly strive to better themselves, but if Israel is anything less than perfect, then everyone jumps all over them in order to please Israel's oil-holding neighbors.  On the evening of 9/11/01 did you see one single nation stand up to the US and remind them to &quot;show restraint&quot;?  When countries questioned the US's treatment of the terrorist suspect, did they start looking into our internal matters and telling us what we should be doing in various neighborhoods with our various citizens?  Israel is no less civilized than any other democracy, but they are constantly under the microscope like they are some sort of nuisance to society.<br>
<br>
&quot;Israeli Arabs may have &quot;full citizenship&quot; but they are not equal citizens.&quot;<br>
<br>
They are equal citizens.  The link you provided me could have had been easily mistaken for an article describing minorities in any democratic country, including the US.  Israel has the same problems as the US when it comes to minority relations.  If the US screws up and skips fixing up an African-American neighborhood, then that doesn't mean the US has lost its democratic status or that the people of that neighborhood all of a sudden lose citizenship status.  It just means that they need to work harder on meeting everyone's needs.  How come when America does it they just need to fix things, but when Israel does it they are compared to nazis or South Africa?  Israel has a lot of problems to fix, I'll agree with that, but it seems that they are being held to a higher standard than any other nation on this planet.  If they aren't the perfect wonderland where their minorities are concerned or they don't sit by and allow people to throw grenades into their preschools, then they aren't worthy of existence.  Israel knows they have internal problems, and the people there are on the road to gradually fixing them.  Rome wasn't built in a day, and neither was Israel.  At least they are working towards fixing these problems, so they are on the right track. <br>
<br>
&quot;Blah blah blah.. This little tidbit is always dragged out, but it's moot (in my opinion). So is &quot;we won the land in war fair and square so it's ours&quot;. I thought we as human beings had moved beyond this whole mode of thinking. There are people living there, who have been for generations. They haven't been absorbed into other countries, so unless you're going to come up with some sort of forced evacuation plan, you have to deal with them being there.. and they are human beings, they deserve some sort of basic level of consideration, again if you're claiming to be this great &quot;Western-style&quot; democracy.&quot;<br>
<br>
First of all Kate, I like you and respect you, and I try to show you the common courtesy of not referring to your statements as &quot;blah blah blah&quot;.  The fact that the Palestinians never had claims to this land is a very valid point.  It isn't like the situation with the Native Americans where they were living all over this land that nobody else owned, and then were slaughtered.  There has always been ownership of that land since the Palestinians have been there, and their name was never on the deed, so to speak.  If the Native Americans showed up after the colonists, then the story would have a whole different twist.  They also are being treated as human beings, more so by the Israeli government than any other government that claims to care about them.  Since when did &quot;nonhumans&quot; gain the right to vote?  Israel had every excuse in the world as to why they could have forced their Arab citizens into exile, or why they could have gotten away with killing many of them.  Instead they allowed them to stay and live among the Jewish citizens.  The Arab population just moved from government to government, but the ones who chose to stay got to do so.  Yes, there are problems being the minority like with the US, but their citizens also have the option to control their own destiny like with the US.  <br>
<br>
&quot;I guess I was thinking more internationally, such that the safeguards couldn't be so easily overturned.. International monitoring, an international presence, whatever it would take.. &quot;<br>
<br>
This has been tried, and it has failed.  It failed in the 1920's when Great Britain reneged on their treaty and issued the White Papers that restricted Jewish immigration to the very land they were promised.  It failed when Great Britain took 4/5 of the land promised to Israel in the treaty and turned it over to the Arabs in order to form Jordan.  It failed in 1967 when all the countries who promised to protect Israel turned the other way when several Arab countries publicly announced that they were moving into attack.  The US didn't step up until after the 1967 war because they realized how strong Israel was on their own, and they wanted a strong and powerful ally.  Before then, the US couldn't care less about Israel.  The reason Israel can't rely on others as a safeguard is because they have all failed the trust test.  Israel has discovered that they can only rely on themselves, and then just hope that others can come to back them up.<br>
<br>
&quot;Okay, you only read the first line of my post. I meant that it doesn't justify oppressing somebody else. Obviously we never want to forget history, so we won't repeat our mistakes. Here we've made such a strong attachment to history, we're repeating it and don't even realize it.&quot;<br>
<br>
I agree that there is no justification for oppression.  However oppression will be the end result when someone is put into a position to possibly defend themselves.  If everyone in your neighborhood started committing crimes on a regular basis, then that would require larger police presence.  The constant intervention by the police to prevent more crimes and the shootouts with criminals in the middle of your street that cause stray bullets to fly into living rooms would be characterized as oppression by the residents in your neighborhood.  The people who are the most outspoken against the police are the ones who are always getting into trouble with them.  Usually the response to these people by the public is &quot;stop breaking the law&quot;.<br>
<br>
&quot;I hope that would be true.. but judging from Human Rights reports in the area, I can't be confident it would be.&quot;<br>
<br>
The Human Rights reports have nailed both sides.  I'm not arguing that there are no violations by the Israeli soldiers.  I think it is wrong to punish a family for something their relative did by bulldozing their house and leaving them homeless.  I am not afraid to admit that here, and this is one of many things that Israel needs to stop.  I understand why they are doing it, but it doesn't make it okay.  But it wouldn't be happening if the terrorism didn't exist, and it doesn't happen to the Arab-Israeli citizens because they are rarely the ones committing acts of terror.  The IDF didn't have such a strong presence in the territories until the intifada started in 2000.  The territories were under PA rule.  When the terrorism gets bad, the IDF increases its presence.  When the terrorism hits a lull, then the troops start to pull out of these areas.  You would think common sense would prevail for the terrorists who live in these territories, and it is common sense for many of the Palestinians living in these territories because the terrorism approval rating has dropped significantly lately.   Israel has already proved that when terrorism lessens, then so does their presence.<br>
